Abbreviation: id: Player Identifier span: Career Span (Years Active) matches: Number of Matches Played innings: Number of Innings Played not_out: Times Not Out runs: total Runs Scored high_score: Highest Score in an Innings average_score: Batting Average ball_faced: Balls Faced by the Batsman strike_rate: Batting Strike Rate 100s: Centuries Scored 50: Half-Centuries Scored 0s: Ducks (Dismissed Without Scoring) 4s: Fours Hit 6s: Sixes Hit sp_bowling: Career Span (Years Active) bbi_bowling: Best Bowling in Innings (Best Figures in a Single Innings) bbm: The best bowling match by the player bl: The total number of balls bowled by the player bwa_bowling:The bowling average of the player bwe: The economy rate of the player bwsr: Bowling Strike Rate (Average Balls Bowled Per Wicket Taken) cd: The number of times the player has achieved a 5-wicket haul fw_bowling:The number of times the player has taken 4 wickets in an innings) fwk: The number of times the player has taken a wicket with their first ball in an innings in: The total number of innings bowled by the player md: Maiden Overs Bowled mt: The number of matches played by the player ov: The total number of overs bowled by the player pr_bowling: The number of times the player has achieved a 3-wicket haul tw: The total number of wickets taken by the player wk_bowling: Wickets Taken (in Bowling) bbad: Best Bowling Average Against a Team (as an All-Rounder) bbi_allrounder: Best Bowling in Innings (as an All-Rounder) bta: The number of balls to boundary against the player (Likely the number of balls bowled that resulted in boundaries) bwa_allrounder:The number of balls with a wicket taken by the player (as an All-Rounder) ct: Catches Taken (as a Fielder) fw_allrounder: Five-Wicket Hauls (as an All-Rounder) hn: Highest Score in an Innings (Context-Specific, could relate to batting) hs: Highest Score in a Series pr_allrounder: Player Rating (Specific to All-Rounder Performance) rn: Runs (Context-Specific, likely related to runs conceded in bowling or scored in batting) st: Stumpings Made (as a Wicketkeeper) wk_allrounder: Wickets Taken (as an All-Rounder) sp_allrounder: years active name: Player Name gender: Player Gender bating_style: Batting Style bowling_style: Bowling Style playing_role: Playing Role (e.g., Batsman, Bowler, All-Rounder) country_id: Country Identifier country: Country Name

Exploratory analysis:

Average Batting Strike Rate by Country in T20 Cricket

avg_strike_rate_by_country <- t20 %>%
  group_by(country) %>%
  summarise(AverageStrikeRate = mean(strike_rate, na.rm = TRUE))

# Create a bar plot
ggplot(avg_strike_rate_by_country, aes(x = reorder(country, AverageStrikeRate), y = AverageStrikeRate, fill = country)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  dark_theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Average Batting Strike Rate by Country in T20 Cricket",
       x = "Country",
       y = "Average Strike Rate") +
  coord_flip() 
## Inverted geom defaults of fill and color/colour.
## To change them back, use invert_geom_defaults().

Comments: The above bar chart shows the average batting strike rate for T20 cricket players from different countries. The strike rate is a measure of how quickly players score runs. In countries at the top, like Pakistan and India, their players tend to score faster on average than those from countries with shorter bars, like Zimbabwe and Bangladesh, at the bottom.

Role-based Performance in T20 Cricket

#without label
avg_performance_by_role <- t20 %>%
  group_by(playing_role) %>%
  summarise(AverageScore = mean(runs, na.rm = TRUE),
            AverageStrikeRate = mean(strike_rate, na.rm = TRUE))


ggplot(avg_performance_by_role, aes(x = AverageScore, y = AverageStrikeRate, color = playing_role)) +
  geom_point(size = 4) +
  dark_theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Batter Performance in T20 Cricket",
       x = "Average Score",
       y = "Average Strike Rate") +
  theme(legend.position = "right") 

average_wickets <- t20 %>%
  filter(playing_role %in% 
           c("bowler", "bowling allrounder", "allrounder")) %>%
  group_by(playing_role) %>%
  summarise(AverageWickets = mean(wk_bowling, na.rm = TRUE))

# Create a bar chart
ggplot(average_wickets, aes(x = playing_role, y = AverageWickets, fill = playing_role)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Average Wickets Taken by Role", x = "Player Role", y = "Average Wickets") +
  dark_theme_minimal()

Comments: This graph represents average wickets taken by playing roles, as seen, surprisingly bowling all-rounders take higher wickets than bowlers.

Bowling Performance in T20 Cricket

bowling_data <- t20 %>%
  filter(!is.na(runs) & !is.na(wk_bowling) & !is.na(ov) & ov > 0) %>%
  group_by(playing_role) %>%
  summarise(AverageEconomyRate = mean(runs/ov, na.rm = TRUE),
            TotalWickets = sum(wk_bowling, na.rm = TRUE))

# Create the scatter plot
ggplot(bowling_data, aes(x = AverageEconomyRate, y = TotalWickets, color = playing_role)) +
  geom_point(size = 5) +
  dark_theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Bowling Performance in T20 Cricket",
       x = "Average Economy Rate",
       y = "Total Wickets Taken",
       color = "Playing Role")

Top 3 Performers in Each Role

top_performers <- t20 %>%
  group_by(playing_role) %>%
  top_n(3, runs) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(desc(runs))

# Plotting
ggplot(top_performers, aes(x = reorder(name, runs), y = runs, fill = playing_role)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip() +
  dark_theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Top 3 Performers in Each Role in T20 Cricket",
       x = "Player",
       y = "Runs")

Comments: This bar graph shows the top 3 players for each playing role. This graph makes us understand which player role has the top performance

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)


role_counts <- t20 %>%
  group_by(playing_role) %>%
  summarise(count = n())

#  playing roles
custom_order <- c("opening batter", "top-order batter", "middle-order batter", "batter",
                  "bowler",
                  "wicketkeeper batter",
                  "batting allrounder", "bowling allrounder", "allrounder")


role_counts$playing_role <- factor(role_counts$playing_role, levels = custom_order)


ggplot(role_counts, aes(x = playing_role, y = count, fill = playing_role)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  dark_theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  labs(title = "Count of Playing Roles in T20 Dataset",
       x = "Playing Role",
       y = "Count") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set3") # This is to add different colors for readability

BASIC CLEANUP

# Columns with 100% NA values
na_columns <- sapply(t20, function(x) mean(is.na(x))) == 1
names(na_columns[na_columns == TRUE])
## [1] "bl"            "pr_bowling"    "pr_allrounder"
cols_with_all_NA <- sapply(t20, function(x) all(is.na(x)))
t20_cleaned <- t20[, !cols_with_all_NA]


t20_cleaned$high_score_numeric <- as.numeric(gsub("[^0-9]", "", t20_cleaned$high_score))



#specific category:
t20_cleaned <- t20_cleaned %>%
  mutate(consolidated_role = case_when(
    grepl("wicketkeeper", playing_role, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "WicketKeeper Batter",
    grepl("batting allrounder", playing_role, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "Batting Allrounder",
    grepl("bowling allrounder", playing_role, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "Bowling Allrounder",
    grepl("allrounder", playing_role, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "Allrounder",  
    grepl("batter", playing_role, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "Batter",
    grepl("bowler", playing_role, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "Bowler",
    TRUE ~ "Other" 
  ))

t20 <- t20_cleaned

graph it out:

library(ggplot2)

# Calculate the count of each consolidated role
consolidated_role_counts <- t20 %>%
  group_by(consolidated_role) %>%

# Calculate boundary rate, avoiding division by zero
batters_only <- t20[t20$consolidated_role == "Batter", ]

batters_only$boundary_rate <- with(batters_only, ifelse(ball_faced > 0, (`4s` + `6s`) / ball_faced, 0))
batters_only$century_rate <- with(batters_only, ifelse(innings > 0, `100s` / innings, 0))
batters_only$not_out_rate <- with(batters_only, ifelse(innings > 0, not_out / innings, 0))
batting_data <- batters_only[, c("boundary_rate", "century_rate", "not_out_rate", 
                                 "average_score", "strike_rate", "high_score_numeric")]

normalized_batting_data <- scale(batting_data)
library(cluster)

# silhouette method
sil_width <- numeric(10) 

for (k in 2:10) {
  km <- kmeans(normalized_batting_data, centers=k)
  ss <- silhouette(km$cluster, dist(normalized_batting_data))
  sil_width[k] <- mean(ss[, "sil_width"])
}

# number of clusters 
k <- which.max(sil_width)
print(paste("The optimal number of clusters is:", k))
## [1] "The optimal number of clusters is: 2"
# Plot the silhouette widths 
plot(2:10, sil_width[-1], type='b', xlab="Number of Clusters", ylab="Average Silhouette Width", main="Silhouette Method for Determining k")

player_clusters_by_team <- batters_only %>%
  group_by(country, cluster) %>%
  summarise(number_of_players = n(), .groups = 'drop')%>%
  spread(cluster, number_of_players, fill = 0)%>%
    mutate(country_abbreviation = case_when(
    country == "Afghanistan" ~ "AFG",
    country == "Australia" ~ "AUS",
    country == "Bangladesh" ~ "BAN",
    country == "England" ~ "ENG",
    country == "India" ~ "IND",
    country == "Ireland" ~ "IRE",
    country == "Newziland" ~ "NZ", 
    country == "Pakistan" ~ "PAK",
    country == "South Africa" ~ "SA",
    country == "Sri Lanka" ~ "SL",
    country == "West Indies" ~ "WI",
    country == "Zimbabwe" ~ "ZIM",
    TRUE ~ country 
  ))

library(tidyr)

# Reshape the data to long format
player_clusters_long <- player_clusters_by_team %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(`1`, `2`), names_to = "cluster", values_to = "number_of_players") %>%
  mutate(cluster = recode(cluster, `1` = "Cluster 1", `2` = "Cluster 2")) # rename clusters

# Now plot using the reshaped data

library(dplyr)

wc_results$Team1 <- as.character(wc_results$`Team 1`)
wc_results$Team2 <- as.character(wc_results$`Team 2`)

# binary target variable indicating whether the team of interest won
wc_results$winner_binary <- ifelse(wc_results$Winner == wc_results$`Team 1`, 1, 0)

# Convert Team1 and Team2 to factors if they are categorical
wc_results$Team1 <- as.factor(wc_results$Team1)
wc_results$Team2 <- as.factor(wc_results$Team2)

# Step 2: Split the data into training and testing sets
set.seed(123) # for reproducibility
training_indices <- sample(1:nrow(wc_results), size = 0.7 * nrow(wc_results))
train_data <- wc_results[training_indices, ]
test_data <- wc_results[-training_indices, ]

library(splitstackshape)
## Warning: package 'splitstackshape' was built under R version 4.3.1
dat <- stratified(wc_results, group = c("1_Team1", "2_Team1", "1_Team2", "2_Team2"), size = 0.2, bothSets = TRUE)

train_data <- dat[[2]]
test_data <- dat[[1]]

# logistic regression model
model <- glm(winner_binary ~ `1_Team1` + `2_Team1` + `1_Team2` + `2_Team2`, data = train_data, family = "binomial")

# Predict on test data
predictions <- predict(model, newdata = test_data, type = "response")
predicted_classes <- ifelse(predictions > 0.6, 1, 0)

# Convert predictions
test_data$winner_binary <- factor(test_data$winner_binary, levels = c(0, 1))
predicted_classes <- factor(predicted_classes, levels = c(0, 1))

lg_conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(data = predicted_classes, reference = test_data$winner_binary)
lg_conf_df <- as.data.frame.matrix(lg_conf_matrix$table)

library(xgboost)

wc_results$winner_binary <- ifelse(wc_results$Winner == wc_results$`Team 1`, 1, 0)


numeric_predictors <- wc_results[, c("1_Team1", "2_Team1", "1_Team2", "2_Team2")]


set.seed(123)  
training_indices <- sample(1:nrow(wc_results), size = 0.7 * nrow(wc_results))
train_data <- numeric_predictors[training_indices, ]
test_data <- numeric_predictors[-training_indices, ]

train_labels <- wc_results$winner_binary[training_indices]
test_labels <- wc_results$winner_binary[-training_indices]

# Create DMatrix objects for XGBoost
dtrain <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(train_data), label = train_labels)
dtest <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(test_data), label = test_labels)


params <- list(
  booster = "gbtree",
  objective = "binary:logistic",
  eta = 0.3,
  max_depth = 6,
  subsample = 0.8,
  colsample_bytree = 0.8
)

# Train the model
xgb_model <- xgb.train(params = params, data = dtrain, nrounds = 100)

#Make predictions
predictions <- predict(xgb_model, dtest)
predicted_classes <- ifelse(predictions > 0.6, 1, 0)

#Convert predictions to factors for the confusion matrix calculation
predicted_classes <- factor(predicted_classes, levels = c(0, 1))
test_labels <- factor(test_labels, levels = c(0, 1))


xg_conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(predicted_classes, test_labels)
print(xg_conf_matrix)
